    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  In the N-degron pathway, ATE1 transfers the amino acid L-arginine (L-Arg) from Arg-tRNA\n                  <jats:sup>Arg</jats:sup>\n                  to N-terminal (Nt) residues of cellular proteins. The resulting Arg/N-degrons bind the autophagic receptor p62/SQSTSM-1/Sequestosome-1 to induce lysosomal degradation of various biomaterials. Here, we demonstrate that the chemical mimetics of Arg/N-degrons, termed autophagy-targeting ligands (ATLs), can induce lysosomal degradation of SARS-CoV-2 (severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus-2) via p62-mediated macroautophagy. In Vero E6 cells infected with SARS-CoV-2, ATLs promoted p62 self-polymerization and enhanced LC3 synthesis and lipidation, leading to viral sequestration within autophagosomes for lysosomal degradation. In transgenic mice overexpressing human angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2), oral administration of ATL1014 inhibited viral replication and increased viability. In a Syrian hamster model, ATL1014 attenuated viral replication in the lungs and demonstrated efficacy in inflammatory lesions and pulmonary congestions. These results identify the N-degron pathway as a potential target for a host-targeting strategy (HTS) against a broad spectrum of viruses.\n                </jats:p>",
    "DOI": "10.1101/2025.09.01.673409",
